Why do we come to this place, Hiroshima? It is to ponder the terrible forces unleashed in the not-too-distant past; to mourn the dead, including more than 100,000 Japanese men, women and children, thousands of Koreans and more than a dozen American prisoners of war. Their spirits speak to us. They urge us to look inward, to contemplate who we are and who we could be in the future.
It is not the fact of war that sets Hiroshima apart from the rest. It is the historical remnants that tell us it is not the fact of war that distinguishes Hiroshima from the rest. Violent conflict emerged with the first humans. Our early ancestors learned to make blades out of flint and javelins out of wood, and they used these tools not only for hunting but also against these same humans. On every continent, the history of civilization is filled with wars. Driven by grain shortages and the desire for gold, as well as by nationalist and religious fervor, war has been forced upon them. Empires have risen and fallen. People have been subjugated and liberated. And at each turn, innocent people have suffered, and their names have been forgotten in the course of time as countless victims have been created.
The World War, with its brutal conclusion at Hiroshima and Nagasaki, was a war between two of the richest and most powerful nations. Until then, their civilization had given us the world's greatest cities and the greatest art. Their thinkers had advanced notions of justice, harmony, and truth. But this war was as much due to the basic instinct for domination and conquest as it was to the simplest forms of inter-tribal conflict. In other words, old patterns were amplified by new capabilities. And without any new constraints. Over the course of a few years, roughly 60 million people died. Men, women and children, no different than us, were shot, beaten, taken away, bombed, imprisoned, starved, poisoned and killed.

