In many places around the world, this war is documented. There are memorials that tell the story of courage and bravery, tombs and uninhabited camps that speak for the wrongs that are too bad to mention. But this image of the mushroom cloud rising in the sky reminds us more than ever of the contradictions that lie at the heart of humanity. The characteristics that make us human - our ideas, our imagination, our language, our tool-making and our ability to distinguish ourselves from nature and to make it bend to our will - these are the very things that have given us the capacity to wreak unparalleled destruction.
How often material progress and social innovation have robbed us of our ability to judge this truth. And how easy it is for us to learn the legitimacy of violence in the name of some noble cause. Every great religion promises love, peace, and a path to justice. But no religion has ever spared its followers from claiming that their faith permits them to kill. A nation develops with a narrative that unites people in sacrifice and cooperation while anticipating amazing feats. But that same narrative has frequently been used to oppress and dehumanize those who are different from us.
Science makes it possible for us to communicate across oceans, to fly above the clouds, to cure diseases and to understand the universe. But the same discoveries can also be transformed into more efficient killing machines.

